<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-05-29T21:29:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-05-29T21:29:00-05:00" n="353" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d353">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 837.00/641.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-29T21:00:00-05:29">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">May</hi> 29, 1912—9 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>In pursuance of your May 29, I saw the President, who declared that he
                            recognized our rights under the circumstances named. He added emphatic
                            appreciation of our Government’s “fine attitude” throughout present
                            crisis, which he says has been worth more to him than his entire
                            army.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Beaupré</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>